# Asanify Client Design System Rules

Use this rule when implementing UI from Figma via MCP tools.

## Tech Stack and Runtime Baseline

- Framework: Vue 3 SFCs, Vue Router 4, Vuex 4.
- UI library: Vuetify 3 (primary), with Bootstrap CSS loaded globally.
- Build: Vue CLI 5 + webpack (`vue-cli-service`, `vue.config.js`).
- Styling: global CSS, global SASS, component `<style scoped>`, Vuetify utility classes.
- Icons: Material Design Icons (`mdi-*`) via `v-icon`; some SVG image icons.

## Token System (Use Existing Sources First)

Primary token sources:

1. Vuetify theme colors in `src/plugins/vuetify.js` (`theme.themes.light.colors`).
2. Global properties in `src/plugins/helpers.js` (`$asanifyBlue`, `$asanifyRed`, etc.).
3. CSS variables in `src/main.css` (`--asanify-blue`, `--asanify-red`).
4. Typography in `src/base.sass` (`$body-font-family: "Quicksand"`).

Rules:

- Reuse existing color tokens before introducing new hex values.
- Prefer Vuetify theme color names (`primary`, `asanifyBlue`, etc.) where possible.
- If a new cross-app token is needed, add it to `src/plugins/vuetify.js` and mirror it in `src/plugins/helpers.js` only when templates rely on `$...` globals.
- There is no token build pipeline (no style-dictionary/theming transform). Keep token changes explicit and local to these files.

## Component Architecture Conventions

- App shell pattern: `src/App.vue` composes `core-system-bar`, `core-app-bar`, `core-drawer`, `core-view`, `core-footer`.
- Shared building blocks live in `src/components/core/` and `src/components/base/`.
- Global shared components are registered in `src/components.js`.
- Feature views live in feature folders under `src/components/` (for example `People`, `RunPayroll`, `Expenses`, `Leave`).
- Many pages use `BasicPageLayout` (`src/components/core/BasicPageLayout.vue`) for breadcrumbs/title/tabs.

Rules:

- For shared/reusable UI, implement in `src/components/core/` (or `base/` if foundational) and register globally only if needed across many features.
- For feature-specific UI, keep code inside that feature folder.
- Keep naming aligned with current conventions: `Core*`, `V*` wrappers, `*Page`, `*Selector`.

## Routing and Code-Splitting Rules

- Route definitions are centralized in `src/router/routes.js`.
- Lazy loading with webpack chunk names is standard (`import(/* webpackChunkName: "..." */ ...)`).

Rules:

- Add new screens as lazy routes with meaningful chunk names.
- Preserve existing route meta usage (`requiresAuth`, `requiresAdmin`, `requiresNotHr`, `requiresWeb`).

## Styling and Responsive Rules

- Global styles: `src/main.css` and `src/App.vue` style block.
- RTL support: `src/assets/styles/rtl.css` (loaded in `src/main.js`).
- Responsive behavior commonly uses `$vuetify.display.*` and utility classes (`d-md-flex`, `d-sm-none`, etc.).

Rules:

- Prefer Vuetify props/utilities and existing utility classes over custom CSS for layout/spacing.
- Use scoped styles for feature-local tweaks; use global CSS only for app-wide behavior or Vuetify overrides.
- Preserve RTL behavior for any directional UI; validate icon mirroring behavior where relevant.
- Reuse `main.css` CSS variables and typography settings before introducing one-off style values.

## Asset and Media Rules

- Primary app assets live in `src/assets/`; PWA icons in `public/manifest.json` and root `icons/`.
- Asset usage style is mixed: static `@/assets/...` and dynamic `require(...)`.
- Web compression is enabled in `vue.config.js` via `CompressionPlugin` when `VUE_APP_PLATFORM === 'web'`.
- Static downloadable templates are configured through env vars (many S3 URLs).

Rules:

- Prefer colocated static imports from `@/assets` for predictable bundling.
- Use dynamic `require` only for truly data-driven asset paths.
- Do not hardcode external asset URLs in components when an env-driven value already exists.

## Icon System Rules

- Default icon system is MDI via `v-icon` and `mdi-*` names.
- Navigation icon definitions are centralized in `src/navigationData.js`.
- `src/components/core/Drawer.vue` supports either `link.icon` (MDI) or `link.image` (custom SVG).

Rules:

- Default to MDI for new UI icons.
- Use kebab-case `mdi-*` names and keep icon metadata in navigation config for nav items.
- Use image icons only when required by branding or unsupported glyphs.

## Project Organization Expectations

- `src/components/` is feature-oriented; avoid creating parallel architecture patterns.
- Keep business logic in existing feature modules and shared helpers/plugins.
- No Storybook/component catalog is present; use in-repo Vue examples and existing pages as reference.

## Figma MCP Implementation Workflow

When converting Figma designs:

1. Map colors to Vuetify theme or existing global color tokens.
2. Map typography to Quicksand-based system from `src/base.sass`.
3. Build layouts with Vuetify grid/components first; add minimal custom CSS.
4. Prefer existing shared components (`core`, `base`, globally registered components) before creating new ones.
5. Check responsive states using `$vuetify.display.*`.
6. Check RTL impacts for alignment and directional icons.
7. Use MDI icons unless a specific asset icon already exists in `src/assets`.

## Guardrails

- Do not introduce a second styling paradigm (for example CSS-in-JS) in this repo.
- Do not bypass token sources with widespread hardcoded colors unless intentionally one-off.
- Do not add Storybook-first patterns; this codebase is route/page-driven.
- Keep changes consistent with Vue SFC + Vuetify conventions already in use.
